Caesar Cipher Script
This Python script implements the Caesar Cipher encryption and decryption technique. 
The Caesar Cipher is a substitution cipher where each letter in the plaintext is shifted a certain number of places down or up the alphabet. 
This simple encryption method is useful for learning basic cryptographic concepts.

-> Features
*/Encryption and Decryption: Perform both encryption and decryption using the Caesar Cipher.
*/Custom Shift Values: Specify the shift value to control the amount of displacement in the cipher.

-> How It Works
The script uses a user-defined shift value to transform the input text. 
Positive shift values encrypt the message by shifting characters forward in the alphabet, while negative shift values decrypt the message by shifting characters backward.

Usage
Clone the Repository:

bash
Copy code
git clone https://github.com/yourusername/your-repository.git
cd your-repository
Run the Script:

bash
Copy code
python caesar_cipher.py
Input Prompts:

Enter your message: Provide the text you want to encrypt or decrypt.
Enter the shift value: Specify a positive integer for encryption or a negative integer for decryption.
Enter 'encrypt' or 'decrypt': Choose the mode of operation.
Example
To encrypt the message "HelloWorld" with a shift value of 3:

Input: HelloWorld, 3, encrypt
Output: KhoorZruog
To decrypt the message "KhoorZruog" with a shift value of -3:

Input: KhoorZruog, -3, decrypt
Output: HelloWorld
Notes
The script handles both uppercase and lowercase letters.
Non-alphabetical characters are not affected by the cipher and are preserved in the output.
